    </div>

    <!-- SECTION 6: SIDE EFFECTS -->
    <h2>Side Effects and Drug Interactions</h2>

    <p>Berberine is generally well-tolerated at recommended doses, but it is not side-effect-free. Understanding the potential adverse effects and drug interactions is essential for safe supplementation. The side effect profile is dose-dependent — most issues occur at higher doses or when berberine is taken on an empty stomach.</p>

    <h3>Common Side Effects</h3>

    <p>Gastrointestinal symptoms are by far the most common side effects, affecting approximately 10-15% of users. These include diarrhea, constipation, flatulence, abdominal cramping, and nausea. GI side effects are typically transient — they occur most frequently during the first 1-2 weeks of supplementation and often resolve with continued use. Taking berberine with meals and using a gradual dose escalation protocol (starting at 500mg/day and increasing over 2 weeks) significantly reduces the incidence and severity of GI symptoms.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="alert-circle" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>GI Disturbance (10-15%)</h3>
        <p>Diarrhea, constipation, flatulence, nausea, and cramping. Most common in the first 2 weeks. Mitigated by taking with meals and starting at a lower dose.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="activity" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Hypoglycemia Risk</h3>
        <p>Berberine lowers blood sugar. Combined with diabetes medications, this can cause dangerously low glucose. Monitor blood sugar carefully, especially when starting.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="heart" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Low Blood Pressure</h3>
        <p>Berberine has mild vasodilatory effects and can lower blood pressure. People already on antihypertensive medications should monitor blood pressure when adding berberine.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="alert-triangle" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Headache and Fatigue</h3>
        <p>Reported infrequently. Usually associated with blood sugar changes in the first week. Typically resolves with continued use and stable dosing.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3>Drug Interactions</h3>

    <p>Berberine is metabolized by cytochrome P450 enzymes (CYP2D6, CYP3A4, CYP2C9) and can alter the metabolism of drugs processed through the same pathways. The following interactions are clinically significant:</p>

