    <!-- SECTION 9: WHO SHOULD NOT TAKE BERBERINE -->
    <h2>Who Should NOT Take Berberine</h2>

    <p>Despite its strong safety profile in healthy adults, berberine is contraindicated in several populations. These contraindications are based on known pharmacological effects and should be taken seriously. If you fall into any of the following categories, do not take berberine without explicit physician approval.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="alert-triangle" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Pregnant Women</h3>
        <p>Berberine can cross the placental barrier and has been shown to cause uterine contractions in animal studies. It may also interfere with bilirubin metabolism in the fetus, increasing the risk of neonatal jaundice (kernicterus). <strong>Berberine is absolutely contraindicated during pregnancy.</strong></p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="alert-triangle" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Breastfeeding Women</h3>
        <p>Berberine is excreted in breast milk and can be transferred to the infant. Given the potential effects on infant bilirubin metabolism and blood sugar, berberine should not be taken during breastfeeding. <strong>Resume only after weaning.</strong></p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="alert-circle" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Children</h3>
        <p>There are insufficient safety data on berberine supplementation in children. Most clinical trials have enrolled adults only. Do not give berberine supplements to children or adolescents under 18 without pediatrician guidance.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="alert-circle" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Liver Disease</h3>
        <p>Berberine is metabolized by the liver. Individuals with significant liver disease (cirrhosis, active hepatitis) may have impaired berberine metabolism, leading to accumulation and increased risk of adverse effects. Physician supervision is required. Note: berberine may <em>help</em> NAFLD, but this is a different condition from severe liver disease.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="heart" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Low Blood Pressure</h3>
        <p>Berberine has vasodilatory effects and can lower blood pressure. People with hypotension or those taking multiple antihypertensive medications should use berberine cautiously, if at all, due to the risk of symptomatic low blood pressure (dizziness, fainting).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="activity" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Pre-Surgery</h3>
        <p>Berberine may affect blood sugar control, blood pressure, and blood clotting during surgery. Discontinue berberine at least 2 weeks before any scheduled surgical procedure and inform your anesthesiologist that you were taking it.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

